clear. I tried to keep this minimal. Now would you be able to describe what's a project that

00:15:39.479 --> 00:15:47.239
you might be working on, where you would be doing this? So this is really very close to the idea of

00:15:47.239 --> 00:15:53.880
a power analysis. If you were introducing this 0.1% improvement, you could start asking questions

00:15:54.039 --> 00:16:02.440
how likely are we to detect it? And so even in this case, if I just look at how often are my

00:16:03.239 --> 00:16:08.039
B simulations bigger than my A simulations, that's not saying it's statistically significant. It's

00:16:08.039 --> 00:16:17.080
just saying bigger at all. The smaller the change in 100,000 users, 68% of the time it would be

00:16:17.159 --> 00:16:23.239
larger. And you could explore the range of differences that you might observe, like a

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:31.320
95% interval of those potential differences. The very concrete examples that I could give

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:38.119
are like when I'm exploring a new A-B testing method, what I'm going to do is I'm going to

00:16:38.119 --> 00:16:45.400
simulate the test data from 100,000 A-B tests. And then I can start asking very practical questions

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:54.119
from those simulated data, like how often did I detect the superior treatment condition? How long

00:16:54.119 --> 00:16:59.640
did it take to detect the superior treatment condition? How many additional conversions did

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:07.800
we yield because we detected the better experience earlier and rolled it out to 100% earlier in the

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:16.599
season? Those are the kind of return on investment questions that I can explore using very basic data

00:17:16.599 --> 00:17:24.040
simulation that my gatekeepers, my stakeholders really care about. They want to know before they

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:29.880
green light using a new statistical method in season. They're going to want to know, does this

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:37.640
detect benefit more often and faster? Does it detect harm more often and faster? And that's

